         "id": "SECTION_local_content",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<h3>Is Gravity Really a Force?</h3>We began by describing gravity based on our current understanding, but this has not always been the case. In the past, gravity was seen as a force, and using this perspective helps explain certain phenomena on Earth, as we will explore",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "424c993c-5af2-4add-954f-35bc5312621f",
                     "text": "NASA/PODAAC",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "",
                        "year": "",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "Konstantino Adamopoulos <i>et al.</i> highlight that various systems in our bodies can be affected by the strength of the gravitational field. Additionally, they discuss how gravity has influenced species evolution, using as an example the arrangement of internal organs in aquatic snakes versus tree-climbing snakes",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "6808958a-781b-4088-85ca-1551c078a2ed",
                     "text": "Adamopoulos, K., et al.",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2021",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  }
               ],
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": "."
            },
            {
               "text": "On the other hand, it’s also possible to consider that there is no \"gravity force\" per se, and that other forces might produce similar effects. For instance, the acceleration measured on the Earth’s surface is not constant and partly results from internal Earth pressure, leading us to observe an acceleration that could be associated with a force stemming from this internal pressure",
               "source": [
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "1df98dc5-523f-42ae-9a69-3e9410849ebb",
                     "text": "Hossenfelder, Sabine",
                     "page": "",
                     "date_time": {
                        "type": "gregory",
                        "year": "2024",
                        "month": "",
                        "day": ""
                     }
                  },
                  {
                     "type": 1,
                     "uuid": "44d06c2e-afbc-4248-95cb-5b507205e532",
